Philda Essop, Netwerk24 Edward Zuma. Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town &ndash; The SAHRC is going to investigate the racist insults President Jacob Zuma&rsquo;s son Edward has directed at former finance minister Pravin Gordhan and former tourism minister Derek Hanekom, Netwerk24 reports.In an open letter, Edward Zuma wrote that Hanekom was a &ldquo;vile dog trained to maul a black skin&rdquo;, eNCA reported on Thursday.&nbsp;He described Gordhan as &ldquo;one of the most corrupt cadres of the ANC who thinks African natives are no better than just being sugar cane cutters who must be forever subservient to a master like him for sustenance&rdquo;.The SA Human Rights Commission said the content of the letter, especially the statements which encouraged hate on the grounds of race, was offensive, upsetting and a clear violation of the right to freedom of expression contained in the Constitution.&nbsp;The SAHRC said it would investigate &ldquo;appropriate&rdquo; actions.&nbsp;On Wednesday evening, Zuma jnr denounced Gordhan and Hanekom as &ldquo;sell outs.&rdquo; Both had asked his father to resign. In recent weeks, Gordhan delivered a sharp critique of &ldquo;corrupt politicians&rdquo;, a reference to president Zuma.Edward wrote they were &ldquo;fronts of white monopoly capital and anti-majority rule&rdquo;.&nbsp;The &ldquo;sell out Gordhan&rdquo; wanted blacks relegated to the sidelines, he claimed. &ldquo;Gordhan and Gandhi views black people as a lower class: K****rs which are subhuman and deserves no status beside that definition.&rdquo;&nbsp;About Hanekom he wrote: &ldquo;It was at the ANC's recent 5th National Policy Conference of the ANC that Derek Hanekom, white monopoly capitalist offspring - who is no better than a vile dog trained to maul a black skin, showed us his true colours.&rdquo;&nbsp;He called him a &ldquo;minority champion white racist Afrikaner&nbsp;anti-majoritarian sell out&rdquo; who &ldquo;vomited on our native black people&rdquo; during the conference&rsquo;s economic transformation commission. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.